{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_fireweed_ver01/data/sn84036287/00340581891/1937120301/1223.xml":{"full_text":"Carbon County News\nO. H. P. SHELLEY, Editor and Owner\nA\nPublished every Friday at Red Lodg^Carbon Oo ;Montana t\nEntered at the Postoffice at Red Lodge, Montana, aa Matter of\nSecond Class, under the Act of Congress of March 6, 1879.\nSubscription\u2014Per year, $2.60; six months, $1.50; three months,\n$.76. All subscriptions payable in advance.\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF CARBON COUNTY\nAND CITY OF RED LODGE\nTELEPHONE NUMBER NINE\nHOW DOES VERMONT DO IT?\nA great deal of newspaper editorial fun,, most of it good\nnatured, has been poked at the two sovereign states of\nMaine and Vermont since the 1936 election on the theory\nthat they are out of step with the rest of the country, in\nreturning Republican pluralities, contrary to the action of\nthe other forty-six states. Some humorists have even\nbeen inclined to look upon them as \"foreign states,\" for\nthe time being at least.\nIt is more than possible however that the laugh may be\non the other side before the second Roosevelt administra\ntion is concluded. At this time when the business reces\nsion has stimulated the demand for more economy in gov\nernment, a greater degree of efficiency and budget balanc\ning, it is surprising to note\u2014surprising at least to the New\nDealers\u2014that little Vermont which takes its Republican\nism straight\u2014is pointing the way for the rest of the coun\ntry. During the past three years Vermont has balanced\nits budget, and has lived well within its income. Indeed\nthe figures prove that during this time it has actually\nshown a profit of $3,600,000. This is not a great sum as\nthey figure things in Washington, but it must be remem\nbered that a million in Vermont looks as big as a billion\nalong the banks of the Potomac. Again Vermont is stead\nily reducing its state debt\u2014which is small, but still a debt.\nNow we note that the President is calling in business\nmen from all over the country to consult with him, in devis\ning means to stimulate business by balancing the budget.\nWhy wouldn't it be a good idea to call the Vermont gover\nnor and the Green Mountain state legislature down to\nWashington and to ask them how they do it? Of course\nthe new Dealers may still consider Vermont foreign terri\ntory, but they get a lot of ideas from Europe, so the?\nought not be averse to getting some from this perennially\nRepublican state.\nThere is a lesson for the G. O. P. here, too. Vermont has\nworked its way out by using time honored principles of\nsound economics. If Republican local officials in various\nparts of the country will do the same thing within the next\nthree years, things may look better for the party in 1940.\nQUERY\nnsoluble problems: What do the ants do in wip\nics?\u2014Toronto Star.\nire are no\npi\nThe old fashioned man who drank his coffee out of a saucer may have\nbeen crude but all his furniture was paid for and he usually had a well\nfilled cellar at the beginning of winter.\nA CHANGE IN THE VOCAL SCORE\nA little more than a year ago,, during the closing days of\nthe 1936 campaign, President Roosevelt, running for re\nelection, felicitated the people of the United States on the\nprogress they had made out of the depression under the\ndirection of the New Deal. He reminded his hearers o\nthe smoke of prosperity belching from factory chimneys\nwhich only a few years ago had been lifeless, and he prom\nised that we would go on and on, under the new dispensa\ntion to new heights of economic well being.\nNow, when only a little more than a year has passed, fol\nlowing a break in the stock market which rivals that of\n1929, and a general lull in business, Mr. Roosevelt is quot\ned as having made the statement that nobody would be\npermitted to starve in America this winter.\nHere is another reassuring statement, although the back\nground seems to have changed in the past twelvemonth.\nNevertheless we endorse this statement. Nobody ought\nto be permitted to starve in the United States. None starv\ned in the depth of the depression in 1931 and 1932, and\nhas starved since then. None will be permitted to\nnone\nstarve in the winter which is descending upon us. That\ngoes without saying, and the President's statement of\ncourse is unnecessary but reassuring. Yet the fact re 1\nmains that there seems to be a new vocal score for the\nNew Deal song of victory. We still hope we will go for\nward to new economic heights and each of us is willing to\ndo his bit to bring such a happy situation about. Perhaps\nlittle constructive effort from our national statesmen\nwouldn't be out of place at this political juncture. What\nto need now is a Sir Christopher Wren and not\na\nwe seem\na Santa Claus.\nPresident Roosevelt's statements about our duty to the world may be\nnoble and high minded but somehow or other they remind us of the\npronouncements of Woodrow Wilson before we got into the World War.\nSome of those gals in bathing suits who win beauty prizes must\nhave received their decisions from a packed court.\nThe New York stock exchange seems to have lost the Roosevelt smile.\nSoo-P firppk\nFromberg-Sage WeeK\nHighway is Assured\nAssurance that work would start\ni|l<m road from From\nnext (MV\nberg to Sage Greek was given\nmembers of the Promberg Com-\nmunity club by John Normile,\nChairman of Carbon county com-\n\nEfforts to construct a road be\ntween these two points have been\nmade for 30 years. The project will\nbenefit ranchers in the Sage Creek\narea by enabling them to travel\na direct water grade route to\nPromberg for coal and freight.\nSNOW BRINGS SICKNESS\nMontana's first snow storm of\nstatewide proportions upped the\nnumber of cases of sickness, ac\ncording to reports to the state\nhealth office. Columbia Palls was\nstill in the grip of an influenza epi\ndemic and public meetings were\nbarred. Bozeman reported 30\nchickenpox patients and Great\nFalls 13 whooping cough cases.\nGlacier county is being visited with\n22 cases of measles and 32 cases\nof scarlet fever developed over the\nstate. There were 17 cases of small\npox, 68 of chicken pox and 172 of\ninfluenza developed during the\nweek.\nby James Preston\nMost of Washington's best\nguessers are willing to bet that the\nspecial session of Congress will\nadjourn without having passed a\nsingle major law. The one possible\nexception is that it may make\nsome extremely necessary changes\nin taxes.\nThere are many contributing\nreasons for that forecast, but the\nbiggest is that basic human emo\ntion\u2014fear.\nWhen the last session ended,\nCongressmen were supposed to go\nback home and get the \"feel\" of\nthe country. Then they were to be\nsummoned into special session to\nfinish up the legislative program\nlaid out for them last January.\nThey did go home and they did\nget the \"feel\". But the effect was\njust the opposite of what had been\nhoped. It strengthened rather than\nweakened the tentative convic\ntions of many members that they\nhad been playing with dynamite\nby approving economic experiments\nwhich few people understood.\nAccording to their stories, the\nbiggest thing the Congressmen\nfound \"back home\" was a surpris\ning lack of real optimism. Then,\njust before they headed Washing\ntonward, the business recession be\ngan to make itself felt.\nWith individual optimism miss\ning, and with business forbidden\nby taxes to build up reserves to\ncarry them through a recession, it\nis only natural that the legislators\nshould wonder. Now, for the first\ntime in years, they are dubious\nabout such things as the wage\nhour bill, the \"little TVA's,\" lump\nsum appropriations, and giving the\nPresident virtually unlimited pow\ner to reorganize the federal govern\nment.\nRegardless of what else might\nbe said about these things, they\ndo not stimulate confidence because\nall of them are experiments and\nnobody Tihows for sure what they\nwill do.\nOpening day of any legislative\nsession is just another day to a\nlot of Congressmen. They know it\ntakes about a week to get the Con\ngressional machinery into opera\ntion, so many of the old-timers\u2014\nunless, they hold positions of lea\ndership or committee chairman\nships which demand that they be\npresent\u2014deliberately avoid the\nhullabaloo of opening day.\nThat was as true for the special\nsession as ever. The galleries were\npacked with spectators, but there\nwere empty seats on the floors of\nboth House and Senate.\nInterestingly, though, the greet\nings exchanged by members in the\ncloakrooms and lobbies were less\neffusive and the talk about legis\nlation was more serious.\nIllustrative of the changing\nWashington viewpoint was a con\nference the other day among some\nhighranking office holders. They\ngot around to a discussion of the\nbusiness recession, and the high\nspot was reached when one \"ad\nvanced thinker\" suggested flatly\nthat the situation showed the weak\nnesses of a democratic form of gov\nernment. He wondered whether so\ncialism wouldn't be the answer\u2014\ngovernment ownership and opera\ntion of all business and industry.\nHe got landed on like the pro\nverbial ton of brick. His two most\nbitter critics were men who said\nonly a year ago that our system\nwas a bad one.\nthe Roman Theatre\nFri. Sat., Dec. 3-4. RAINBOW\nNITE SATURDAY! PAT O'\nBRIEN, JOAN BLONDELL, MAR\nGARET LINDSAY in \"BACK IN\nCIRCULATION.\" A murder a day\nkeeps marriage away! And what\na Murder! A Swell-looking Widow!\nJust what Pat needed to keep Joan\nbusy, and keep him single! Added:\n\"DICK TRACY\", Cartoon Fox\nNews! PAL NITE FRIDAY!\n6-6-7.\nLORETTA YOUNG, DON AME\nCHE, BORRAH MINNEVITCH\nHIS HARMONICA RASCALS in\n\"LOVE UNDER FIRE\". Bombers\nroar! Big Guns thunder! But who's\nafraid of Love! Madcap sweet\nhearts living on thrills and laugh\ning at Peril! Added: Musical Com\nedy, Popular Science, color Car\ntoon, News!\nComing! Sun. Mon. Tues., Dec.\n12-13-14. EDDIE CANTOR in\n\"ALI BABA GOES TO TOWN\".\nHold on to your Turbans, folks!\nWe've got something here!\nSun. Mon. Tues., Dec.\nCOLLECTS FRONT PAGES\nAdd to the list of faculty hob\nbies: James M. Holm, instructor in\nSpeech, collects front pages of\nnewspapers. Mr. Holm, who this\nyear joined the faculty of Montana\nState University, probably gets\nthat front page business from his\nfather, a veteran Ohio newspaper\nman who was for years telegraph\neditor of the Ohio Vindicator.\nUse the classifed column.\nXMAS SEAL DRIVE\n'iy-:.\n(Continued from Page 1)\nadicate tuberculosis from our own\nstate. One has only to read the\nbulletins issued by association\nand stories being carried in the\npopular magazine\nLook\", to see what has been done.\nThe records show that 7,974 boys\nand girls in the high schools of\nMontana were given the tubercu\nlin skin test to learn if they had\never had a contact with an active\nesae. All the children who showed\nsuch a recation were promptly X\nrayed in order to tell how far the\ndisease had progressed. That's\nShe went on to say that 95 per\ncent of the funds obtained through\nthis year's Christmas seal drive\nwill be spent for the prevention of\ntuberculosis within the state bor\nders. Five per cent will go to the\nNational Tuberculosis association\nto be used for medical and social\nresearch and to give consultation\nservice to the states.\nPreliminary plans for the local\ndrive, in which it is expected that\nhundreds of the seals will be sold,\nalso include the \"bangle pin\" drive\namong the grade school children,\nin which each contributor will re\nceive a pin signifying that he has\naided in the fight against tubercul\nosis.\nLife\" and\nStating that there has been a\ndefinite reduction of action cases\nof tuberculosis in Montana during\nthe last two years, Mrs, Henrietta\nCrockett of the Montana Tubercul\nosis association urged state-wide\nsupport of the annual Christmas\nseal sale, the funds of which are\nspent for the protection of Montana\nchildren from tuberculosis.\n\"In 1936 there were 220 tuber\nculosis deaths in our state against\n251 for 1935 and 265 for 1934.\nCertainly this decreasing death\nrate is a monument to the actual\neffectiveness of our annual Christ\nmas seal sale,\" she said. \"How\never, when this decline in deaths\nis mentioned, in the same breath\nwe should say that tuberculosis is\nstill a major public health problem,\nalthough this splendid progress in\ncontrol is steadily continuing.\n\"We must remember that each\nyear there are 70,000 deaths caus\ned by tuberculosis in this country\nand tuberculosis is the first cause\namong persons 15 to 45 years of\nage,\" she continued. \"If we link\nthese facts together when we con\nsider our decreases in deaths, we\nget a different picture of our prob\nlem. We know that a great deal\nstill remains to be aceorrmlished.\n99\nThe accumulated funds of this\nsale of Christmas seals will be us\ned to finance the X-ray pictures\nwhich will be' given to the 77 re\nactors to the recent tuberculosis\ntests carried oh in the eight Car\nbon county high schools.\nADVANTAGES OF\n'\u25a0\u25a0Wi\nMARINES CITED\nWhen a young man applies at\na Marine Corps recruiting office\nfor enlistment he is given a numb\ner of pamphlets describing Mar\nine Corps life, and much infor\nmation from the recruiter and of\nten from the recruiting officer in\nperson. These pamphlets and per\nsonal experience stories appeal to\nthe applicant. They are so much\nto his liking that he believes them\nimplicitly. He considers them to\nbe a promise of what he has a\nright to expect if he enlists. In ex\nchange for this promise he gives\nhis own pledge to serve for a per\niod of four years, unless sooner\ndischarged; to hear true faith and\nallegiance to the United States of\nAmerica; and to conduct himself\naccording to the prescribed re\ngulations.\nIn exchange for this very defi\nnite pledge, tne Marine Corps\npromises him certain definite\nrights and benefits. These are\nTravel, Promotion and Increased\nPay, Education, Character Im\nprovement, Sports, and Security\nin Old Age.\nThe question has been asked;\nDoes the Marine Corps keep its\npart of the promise? Is the Mar\nine Corps keeping faith with the\nyoung men who enlist in its ser\nvice\nAn answer to those questions\nhas been prepared from the re\ncords of 100 men enlisted during\nthe year 1932. These records were\nchosen at random from many\nhundreds on file, and the results\nare released by Captain C. C. Gill,\nMarine Corps Recruiting Officer,\n433 Federal Building, Seattle,\nWashington.\nHere is how the Marine Corps\nkept its promises:\nTravel: Seventy-seven of these\nmen were assigned to s\u00e9a duty a\nboard the vessels of the U. S.\nFleet, and visited Honolulu Pan\nama Canal Zone and South and\nCentral American ports. Twenty\nnine went to shore stations in\nforeign countries, such as Guam,\nPhilippine Islands, Shanghai, Peip\ning and Cuba.\nIncreased Pay: During the four\nyear period, fifty-seven of these\nhundred men were promoted to\nvarious higher ranks with addi\ntional pay.\nEducation and Sports: Facilities\nare available .for every man to im\nprove his education and to follow\nwhatever game he likes, without\ncost to himself. A number com\npleted courses in the Marine\nCorps Institute.\nCharacter Improvement is diffi\ncult to define, but by observing the\nconduct of this \"average 1 group,\nthe standing, and by inference, the\nimprovement of the group can be\nestablished. The results at the end\nof the four years showed that on\ndischarge seven were \"bad,\" three\ngood,\" seventeen \"very good\nand sixty-three \"excellent.\" Of\nthis total number thirty-four were\nawarded good conduct medals.\nSeventy-one did not commit a\nsingle offense during the four\nyears, proving that the high re\nquirements are not hard to live up\nto.\nSecui-ity in Old Age: A total of\nfourteen of this original hundred\ndecided to take advantage of this\nby either reenlisting or extending\ntheir enlistments. Transfer to the\nFleet Marine Corps Reserve, at\nhalf pay after twenty years' ser\nvice or transfer to the retired list\nat three-quarters pay after thirty\nyears, offer steady and a sufficient\nincome for old age.\nThus it is seen that the man who\nfulfils his part of the bargain will\nfind that the Marine Corps is al\nways ready to cooperate with him\nfrom the moment that he takes\nthe oath of allegiance until the\nvery end.\nII\n99\nFASHION NOTE\nSock him on the kisser,\nPut him on the pan,\nRoll him in the gutter\u2014\nHe's a business man!\nPillory the sucker.\nPoke him in the eye.\nJump upon his torso\u2014\nHe's a business guy!\nHas he built a business\nTo enormous heights?\nBrand him as a cheater\u2014\nNever mind his rights!\nDoes he give employment?\nIs the pay roll big?\nPut the bum in irons!\nToss him in the brig!\nt\nDoes he pay in taxes\nWhat the law calls for?\nWhy, the dirty reptile\nShould be paying more!\nBlast him in the headlines.\nCharge some crooked acts\nLet this be your slogan:\nAnything but facts!\"\n\nHas he made some money?\nGet his scalp today!\nSay, where does he think he's\nLiving, anyway?\nH. I. PHILLIPS.\nMONTANA IS GAME\nPARADISE IN 1800\nMontana was a game paradise\nat the turn of the 19th. century\nwhen Lewis Clark made their\npioneering expedition through the\nstate, figures released by the\nState Game department reveal.\nLewis Penwell, U. S. Collector\nof customs for Montana, wrote\nGame Warden James IE: Weaver\nthat two hunters, Merriweather\nLewis and Captain William Clark,\non a trip from Great Falls to Three\nForks violently violated the state\nconservation laws by killing 16\nantelope, 43 deer, 8 elk, 9 beaver,\n12 otter, 5 wolves, 3 goats, 1 fox,\n4 geese, 7 bear and 18 buffalo.\nGame guardians momentarily\nwere astonished until they noted\nthat the shooting trip occurred in\nJuly 1805, and that the two migh\nty hunters had to feed 45 men\nwith the spoil during the entire\nmonth of July. Penwell's -search\nof the official records of the ex\npedition revealed that Montana\nwas well supplied with all man\nof wild life in the of\nner\nLewis Clark.\n\"last year,\nGarfield Ranch Aided\nBy Flood Irrigation\nRegistered Ladak alfalfa plus\na flood irrigation system proved\nan unbeatable combination this\nyear for Williamson Brothers on\ntheir place four and one-half miles\nsouthwest of Sand Springs in Gar\nfield county, according to O. A.\nLammers, county extension agent.\nThe 25-acre field of Ladak was\nplanted in 1935 on new breaking\nof blue joint and white sage sod,\nLammers said. An ordinary drill\nwas used with the regular spacing\nand the alfalfa was seeded at the\nrate of two pounds per acre. This\nresulted in a good stand for seed\nproduction.\nIn building the flood irrigation\nsystem, the Williamson brothers\nhired an engineer to do the sur\nveying. Three earth fill dams were\nbuilt in the Dry Fork of Calf\ncreek. These dams required from\n50 to 160 yards of material and\nwere constructed at an estimated\ncost of $75 to $100.\n2,017 STUDENTS AT \"U\"\nEnrollment at Montana State\nUniversity was 2,017 on Nov. 1,\nthe Registrar's office announced\ntoday. This figure is 59 lower than\nthe figure of Nov. 1, 1936. A break\ndown of the figures shows 1,270\nmen and 747 women. Last year\nthere were 1,307 men and 769\nwomen. Freshman registration this\nyear is 703, a drop of 126 from the\n1936 total of 829. Upperclass en\nrollment is 67 higher than it was\nOF\nSTATE IS CITED\nSince the organization of the\nCivilian Conservation Camps in\nApril, 1933, and up to the end of\nOctober of this year, 14,982 Mont\nana boys have been enrolled for\nwork in these camps. During this\nperiod the United States has paid\nto these boys and to their depend\nents a total of more than three\nmillion dollars. The regular month\nly pay for each boy is $30.00, of\nwhich $25.00 is paid to his par\nents or dependents. The remain\ning $5.00 per month is allowed the\nboy for his personal needs in\ncamp. In addition to this cash pay\nment, every boy in camp gets free\nboard, free clothing, medical at\ntention, dental service and some\nschooling of a practical nature.\nFifty-five of the fifty-six coun\nties of the State have boys in CCC\ncamps at the present time. A total\nof twenty camps will be operated\nin the State through the winter of\n1937-38. Ten of these camps are\nmade up of boys from Kentucky,\nand Ohio, and the remaining ten\nare made up exclusively of Mon\ntana boys, numbering in all just\nabout 1,800. The total monthly\npayroll for Montana boys and their\nparents and dependents will there\nfore amount to approximately .$54,\n000\nThe greatest benefit resulting\nfrom the maintenance of thes\u00e9\ncamps is the advantages that it af\nfords to the boys themselves. It\ngives them the opportunity to earn\na monthly income by their own ef\nforts; they work in salubrious sur\nroundings and are fed good whole\nsome food. The practical education\nthey receive is of real constructive\nvalue. It gives the boys courage,\nstrength and hope for lives of fu\nture usefulness.\nThe monthly payment of $26.00\nto their parents and dependents is\nof substantial assistance, and re\nduces the relief load on the tax\npayers of the State.\nIn addition to the cash payments\nto the boys and their dependents,\nthe Government is paying out large\nsums every month for food and sup\nplies for the camps, for supervis\nion and other operating expenses.\nThe bulk of all money spent by the\nGovernment in connection with\nthese camps is expended in the\nState of Montana and results in a\nconsiderable stimulus to business\nalong all lines during twelve\nmonths of the year.\nThe supervision of enrollment\nfor CCC camps is one of the func\ntions of the State Department of\nPublic Welfare and is carried out\nunder the direction of Mrs. Mar\ngaret Best, who has had charge of,\nthis important work for several\nyears.\nMrs. Charles Mattila was bridge\nhostess Monday evening when she\npresided for members of the B.\nB. club. With two tables of con\ntract in Play, Mrs. William De\nBourg, Mrs. Mattila and Miss Abi\ngail Doran held the scoring awards.\nMiss Alice Matthews, instructor\nin the Lovell, Wyo., schools, spent\nThanksgiving vacation with her\nparents, Mr. and Mrs. Harry Mat\nthews, and with friends here.\nMiss Opal Heerwald left to en\nroll for the winter quarter at the\nBillings Business college.\nMr, and Mrs. C. P. Hamrick of\nPiney Dell have as their guests,\nMrs. Rose Currier of Springdale.\nP ARK THEATRE\nWEEKLY PROGRAM\nFri. Sat, Dec. 3-4. DOUBLE\nFEATURE. No 1. BUCK JONES\n(The Action Ace) in \"BOSS OP\nLONELY VALLEY\". Another rip\nroaring western with your favorite\nCowboy Star! No. 2. JAMES\nDUNN, WHITNEY BOURNE in\n\"LIVING ON LOVE\". You all\nknow Jimmy\u2014so we needn't tell\nyou about this picture! RAINBOW\nNIGHT SATURDAY.\nSun., Mon., Tues., Dec. 5-6-7.\nThe two great stars of the \"Thin\nMan,\" stories are here to enter\ntain you again! WILLIAM PO\nWELL\u2014 M YRN A LOY in\n\"DOUBLE WEDDING.\" Meet the\nman who has loads of \"YUMPH!\nThe gayest, giddiest, goofiest\ncomedy ever turned out of Holly\nwood! Also color traveltalk and\nRobert Benchley short and News!\nMatinee Sunday 2 p. m.\nWednesday, Thursday., Dec. 8-9.\nDOUBLE FEATURE No. 1 ANN\nSOTHERN BURGESS MERE\nDITH in \"THERE GOES THE\nGROOM,\" Fast, flippant comedy\nin a 3-way romance with a new\ntwist every minute and a new\nlaugh for every turn! No. 2 KENT\nTAYLOR\u2014IRENE HERVEY in\n\"THE LADY FIGHTS BACK.\nRough and ready romance! Rain\nbow Night Wednesday.\nFri. Sat. Dec. 10-11. DOUBLE\nFEATURE. No. 1 Chester Morris,\nWhitney Bourne in\nFROM GLORY\". The drama of\noutlawed flyers\u2014 thrills excite\nment! No. 2. Robert Wilcox\u2014Doro\nthea Kent in\nQUEEN\". Drama of a society girl\non a daredevil adventure! A swell\nstory of girl who exchanged her\nermine wraps for tights!\n99\n99\nPLIGHT\n\"CARNIVAL\nz\nI-\nWALLUM'S\n\n\nBy EVERETT WALLUM\nBelieve it or not, there'll be\nSpring Fever in Red Lodge to\nnight. That's the title of the Junior\nclass play. Just another instance\nof roses in December.\nDutch Hartwig will be scouting\nthe play. \"If any of those boys\nhave spring fever, I'll sign 'em up\nas high jumpers,\" the coach opin\ned.\nIf you want spring fever-, try\nriding ir. a 19,16 car. The lack of\nsprings will put you in a ward in\nno time.\nOH WELL, THEY PROBABLY\nHAVE SPRING EARLIER AT\nTHE HIGH SCHOOL, WHAT\nWITH EMIL DIMICH ROASTING\nEVERYBODY.\nWe don't know what the students\nwill do to keep warm after Emil\ntalks his way to a diploma.\nIn fact he's chirping so much\nthey're going to present him with\na cheep-skin instead of a sheep\nskin when he graduates.\nFROM WHAT WE'VE SEEN\nOF THE GAY YOUNG HIGH\nSCHOOL BLADES THEY'D\nBE BETTER IN A PLAY CALL\nED \"HEY HEY FEVER.\"\nAnd as he waxes warm in his ar\ndor, he can wail \"I've got that old\nfueling,\nr m\nBut they can't kid us. We know\nspring isn't coming. Floyd Gebo's\nsore finger hasn't started to squeak\n\u00aethe joints yet, as it does when\nXmas jewelry begins to turn green.\nAnd by, the way, we've just\nfound out that they call them\nblades because they're always cut\nting up.\nThe leading female character in\nthe comedy is named Spring,\nwhich is a good name if it's leap\nyear.\nSpring fever, as we understand\nit, is a feeling in the time of the\nyear when a fella is more woozy\nthan wooed.\nTHE THEME SONG FOR THE\nBOY IN LOVE TONIGHT\nSHOULD BE \"I'VE GOT THAT\nOLD FAILING,\nI\n\n99\nAnd Gail hasn't had his spring\nhaircut yet.\nm\nCOME TO THINK OF IT, HE\nHASN'T HAD HIS WINTER\nSHEARING. HE ALWAYS\nWAITS UNTIL NEW YEAR'S\nDAY, BECAUSE THAT'S THE\nTIME THEY HAVE THE BOWL\nGAMES. GAIL PLACES A SOUP\nBOWL ON HIS FOLIAGE AND\nSNIPS AWAY THE FRINGES.\nFUN!\nWe know spring's coming when\nJack McFate takes out his calen\ndar file and starts thumbing over\nthe art masterpieces. He's hardly\nglanced at 'em lately, so we know\nwe're in for a hard winter.\n1\nAnd our toes are starting to curl\nup, which means we've got at least\nfour months of bleak weather in\nthe offing.\nI\nBut that doesn't mean a guy\ncan't have Spring Fever if he wants\nto. It seems that everyone is fall\ning in love this year except the\ncynics. \"Cynic or swim,\" is their\nmotto.\nTHE JUNIORS MAY BE PLAY- 1\nING IN SPRING FEVER, BUT 1\nTHEY'LL THINK IT'S BUCK\nFEVER WHEN THE CURTAIN i\nGOES UP.\nOur idea of an ideal cast for v\nSpring Fever would be members of\ncongress. They might just as well\ndo their sleeping on the stage.\nSpeaking of drowsiness, ho hum\nperiod\nThe United States Civil Service\nCommission announces the follow\ning open competitive examinations:\nSenior Stenographer, Junior Sten\nographer, Senior Typist, Junior\nTypist. These examinations are\nopen to men only. (There are ade\nquate registers of female eligibles.\nApplications must be on file with\nthe Manager, Eleventh U. S. Civil\nService Dist. Seattle, Wash., not\nlater than December 17, 1937.1\nThese examinations are for the]\npurpose of filling existing vacanc-1\nies and future vacancies in, posi-j\ntions requiring similar qualifica-l\ntions in the States of Idaho, Mon-I\ntana, Oregon and Washington.!\nFull information may be obtained!\nfrom th\u00e9 Secretary, Board of U. S.l\nCivil Service Examiners, Post Of-|\nfice, this city, or. the Manager,!\nEleventh U. S. Civil Service Dis-|\ntrict, 456 Federal Office Buildii\nSeattle, Washington.\nPhono your want ad to No. 9.","height":"21735","width":"16431"}}
